Analyzing From Hamilton-Jacobi Point of View 

The Hamilton-Jacobi formalism associated with the NCQM is found by applying
the same procedure previously discussed when considering the NCQFT. We write
the wavefunction in its polar form , substitute into
equation (), and separate its real and imaginary parts. For the real
part we obtain

 
The three new potential terms are defined as
 
 
and
 
The  potential accounts for the noncommutative
classical interactions, while  and  for the quantum effects.
The origin of the  potential is from the kinetic term of the
Hamiltonian, closely related to the case of NCQFT discussed before. Its
definition is identical to the one of the quantum potential in ordinary
Bohmian mechanics, and here we will call it the kinetic quantum
potential. The remaining term, , is the potential that will accounts
for the quantum effects that came from the interaction term, and thus should
be called interaction quantum potential.

The imaginary part of the Schro dinger equation yields
 
which is identical to the equation () for probability conservation,
now written in function of the  and  fields.

Returning to equation (), we see that while and 
